My father had the heart to create a family on every set he was on. He was privileged enough to create a wonderful family on the set of Chesapeake Shores. He kept us updated on what everyone was doing, what was going on, who was having babies, and everything else that was special about their relationships. He loved his cast mates dearly. As time passes, the grief doesn’t get any easier, but life is fragile. We are trying to live every day like it’s our last, and appreciate the time on this beautiful planet that we are lucky to call home. Here’s a picture from Treat’s Celebration of Life of the family 🤍
Another one of Treat’s “wallet photos” ❤️❤️

Dearest Manchester and the mountain community. I just want to say thank you from the bottom of my heart. I want you to know that the kids and I feel your love and your support. I have read every single card and listened to every message and whether you sent something or not it doesn’t matter because I feel you and know that you’re thinking of us and sending us so much love and support. I just want you to know that, and please pass that message on to anyone asking about us. We are devastated but we are strong and we are okay and we are grateful to feel Treat with us everyday.
Thank you also to his fans who continue to reach out with so much love and support and of course to our friends around the country and world who have reached out to us. We are very lucky to live in this special tight knit community and to also have friends all over the planet who are holding us in their thoughts and prayers. From the bottom of my heart (and Gill & Ellie’s) Thank you ❤️🙏❤️

To me it’s always represented a man on a ladder hanging the moon for his love. Interesting happens to be next to his pirates of penzance heart and a little gold plane flying overhead. ❤️✨✨

As we watch the Golden Globes tonight, we are remembering my Dad who was nominated for 3 Golden Globe awards. He was nominated for “Hair” in 1980 as New Star of The Year, “Prince of The City” in 1982 for Best Performance by an Actor in a Motion Picture - Drama, and “A Streetcar Named Desire” in 1985 for Best Performance by an Actor in a Limited Series, Anthology Series, or a Motion Picture Made for Television. We love you, Dad. You’re still shining bright ✨
